<subSubSection id="9AA9651CFFC4FFE8A2AE7AE394A8095B" pageId="13" pageNumber="1225" type="description">
<paragraph id="D20C3697FFC4FFE8A2AE7AE395720BA3" blockId="13.[935,1298,441,466]" box="[935,1298,441,466]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1225">(NINE SPECIES IN FIVE GENERA)</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D20C3697FFC4FFE8A2207AB894A8095B" blockId="13.[809,1425,481,810]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1225">
<emphasis id="E0C7EA85FFC4FFE8A2207AB893D10B86" box="[809,945,482,503]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1225">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Small to large adult-sized slightly ammoniacal 
<taxonomicName id="15B34D14FFC4FFE8A2B1795A941E0867" authorityName="Steenstrup" authorityYear="1857" box="[952,1150,512,534]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Ommastrephidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oegopsida" pageId="13" pageNumber="1225" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Ommastrephidae</taxonomicName>
with ocular, mantle and/ or visceral photophores or photogenic tissues; funnel groove with foveola and lateral pockets; tentacles with carpal locking apparatus; tentacle club with manus horny rings usually with four larger pointed teeth forming a square; four series of suckers on dactylus; lateral suckers of the paralarva proboscis larger or equal in diameter to the central ones; paralarvae with skin sculpture; adult female with multiple seminal receptacles in the buccal membrane.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
